      <article id="node-6" class="node node-article node-promoted node-teaser clearfix" about="/node/6" typeof="sioc:Item foaf:Document">
          <header>
	                  <h2 class="title" property="dc:title" datatype=""><a href="/node/6">An Elegant Way to Build Contact Us Forms</a></h2>
              
              <span class="submitted"><span property="dc:date dc:created" content="2012-09-03T16:54:34+05:30" datatype="xsd:dateTime" rel="sioc:has_creator">Submitted by <span class="username" xml:lang="" about="/user/1" typeof="sioc:UserAccount" property="foaf:name">Anonymous</span> on Mon, 09/03/2012 - 16:54</span></span>
      
          </header>
  
  <div class="content">
    <div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"><p>If you're anything like me then you have problems with those annoying captcha things which appear when you're trying to fill out a form on a website.  Personally speaking, I have a hard time reading them.  Most web developers seem to use either captchas or security questions to prevent their forms from being submitted by spambots.  However, here's a more elegant solution which allows you to get rid of captchas and gives your visitors a more pleasant experience:</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-tags field-type-taxonomy-term-reference field-label-above"><div class="field-label">Tags:&nbsp;</div><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="dc:subject"><a href="/taxonomy/term/9" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel">web development</a></div><div class="field-item odd" rel="dc:subject"><a href="/taxonomy/term/10" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel">tutorial</a></div><div class="field-item even" rel="dc:subject"><a href="/taxonomy/term/11" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel">contact forms</a></div></div></div>  </div>

      <footer>
      <ul class="links inline"><li class="node-readmore first"><a href="/node/6" rel="tag" title="An Elegant Way to Build Contact Us Forms">Read more<span class="element-invisible"> about An Elegant Way to Build Contact Us Forms</span></a></li>
<li class="comment_forbidden last"><span><a href="/user/login?destination=node/6%23comment-form">Log in</a> or <a href="/user/register?destination=node/6%23comment-form">register</a> to post comments</span></li>
</ul>    </footer>
  
    </article> <!-- /.node -->
  <article id="node-5" class="node node-article node-promoted node-teaser clearfix" about="/node/5" typeof="sioc:Item foaf:Document">
          <header>
	                  <h2 class="title" property="dc:title" datatype=""><a href="/node/5">Google Algorithm Shift Brings New Opportunities</a></h2>
              
              <span class="submitted"><span property="dc:date dc:created" content="2012-09-03T14:47:14+05:30" datatype="xsd:dateTime" rel="sioc:has_creator">Submitted by <span class="username" xml:lang="" about="/user/1" typeof="sioc:UserAccount" property="foaf:name">Anonymous</span> on Mon, 09/03/2012 - 14:47</span></span>
      
          </header>
  
  <div class="content">
    <div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"><p>Since the Panda and Penguin updates, many search engine optimisation professionals have struggled to acquire or maintain hire rankings for their clients.  There can be no doubt that the SEO techniques which worked a year ago aren't working today.  Thankfully, however, a clear picture seems to be emerging and if you understand how the new Google algorithm works then there's no reason why you can't enjoy high rankings - even for brand new websites.  In the near future I'll be releasing a new course for members of my Insider Club.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-tags field-type-taxonomy-term-reference field-label-above"><div class="field-label">Tags:&nbsp;</div><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="dc:subject"><a href="/taxonomy/term/5" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel">SEO</a></div><div class="field-item odd" rel="dc:subject"><a href="/taxonomy/term/6" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel">search engine optimisation</a></div><div class="field-item even" rel="dc:subject"><a href="/taxonomy/term/7" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel">Panda update</a></div><div class="field-item odd" rel="dc:subject"><a href="/taxonomy/term/8" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel">Penguin update</a></div></div></div>  </div>

      <footer>
      <ul class="links inline"><li class="node-readmore first"><a href="/node/5" rel="tag" title="Google Algorithm Shift Brings New Opportunities">Read more<span class="element-invisible"> about Google Algorithm Shift Brings New Opportunities</span></a></li>
<li class="comment_forbidden last"><span><a href="/user/login?destination=node/5%23comment-form">Log in</a> or <a href="/user/register?destination=node/5%23comment-form">register</a> to post comments</span></li>
</ul>    </footer>
  
    </article> <!-- /.node -->
  <article id="node-1" class="node node-article node-promoted node-teaser clearfix" about="/node/1" typeof="sioc:Item foaf:Document">
          <header>
	                  <h2 class="title" property="dc:title" datatype=""><a href="/node/1">State of the Internet Marketing Community</a></h2>
              
              <span class="submitted"><span property="dc:date dc:created" content="2012-09-02T22:14:43+05:30" datatype="xsd:dateTime" rel="sioc:has_creator">Submitted by <span class="username" xml:lang="" about="/user/1" typeof="sioc:UserAccount" property="foaf:name">Anonymous</span> on Sun, 09/02/2012 - 22:14</span></span>
      
          </header>
  
  <div class="content">
    <div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"><p>I've just recorded my first State of the Internet Marketing Community address over at <a href="http://www.dcradionetwork.com">www.dcradionetwork.com</a>.  It's an idea that I basically stole from Frank Kern.  I hope you enjoy it and I hope somebody out there appreciates my somewhat alternative viewpoint.  It's at <a href="http://www.dcradionetwork.com">www.dcradionetwork.com</a></p>
</div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-tags field-type-taxonomy-term-reference field-label-above"><div class="field-label">Tags:&nbsp;</div><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="dc:subject"><a href="/taxonomy/term/3" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel">State of the Internet</a></div><div class="field-item odd" rel="dc:subject"><a href="/taxonomy/term/4" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel">marketing community</a></div></div></div>  </div>

      <footer>
